    ROOT CAUSE                                                                  
                                                                                
    comprexx() allocates a fixed‑size array on the stack:                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     char tempname[MAXPATHLEN];          /* MAXPATHLEN == 1024 */               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The argument *fileptr points to the filename supplied on the command line.  
    When the test harness runs the program with a filename consisting of        
    thousands of “a” characters, the length of the filename far exceeds         
    MAXPATHLEN.                                                                 
    strcpy(tempname, *fileptr) copies the entire string without any length      
    check. Because tempname lives on the stack, the copy writes past its        
    1024‑byte boundary, overwriting the saved frame pointer and the return      
    address that sit immediately after the array. When comprexx() returns, the  
    corrupted return address is used, causing the process to jump to an         
    invalid address and raise a segmentation fault – the observed crash.        
                                                                                
    Thus the immediate defect is an unsafe, unbounded write to a fixed‑size     
    stack buffer that does not validate the size of the input filename.         
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    LOCAL FIX                                                                   
                                                                                
    Replace the unsafe strcpy with a bounded copy that guarantees               
    null‑termination and will never write past the end of tempname:             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     -    strcpy(tempname, *fileptr);                                           
     +    /* Copy at most MAXPATHLEN‑1 characters and always NUL‑terminate */   
     +    strncpy(tempname, *fileptr, MAXPATHLEN - 1);                          
     +    tempname[MAXPATHLEN - 1] = '\0';                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or, if the project already pulls in the BSD strlcpy function:               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     -    strcpy(tempname, *fileptr);                                           
     +    strlcpy(tempname, *fileptr, sizeof(tempname));                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
    A minimal additional safety check can be added before the copy:             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     size_t len = strlen(*fileptr);                                             
     if (len >= MAXPATHLEN) {                                                   
         /* reject or truncate as policy dictates */                            
         handle_filename_too_long(*fileptr);                                    
         return;                                                                
     }                                                                          
     strcpy(tempname, *fileptr);   /* now known to be safe */                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This local change eliminates the overflow that directly triggers the        
    crash.                                                                      
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    GLOBAL FIX                                                                  
                                                                                
    The underlying problem is the use of a static stack buffer whose size is    
    derived from a macro that is not tied to any runtime validation.  To        
    prevent the whole class of buffer‑overflow bugs in the program, adopt one   
    of the following architectural changes:                                     
                                                                                
     1 Eliminate fixed‑size stack buffers – allocate the temporary filename     
       dynamically (malloc) based on the actual length of the input string,     
       e.g.                                                                     
                                                                                
        char *tempname = malloc(len + 1);                                       
        if (!tempname) abort();                                                 
        strcpy(tempname, *fileptr);   /* now safe: len+1 bytes are allocated    
        */                                                                      
        … use tempname …                                                        
        free(tempname);                                                         
                                                                                
     2 Reject long inputs early – before calling comprexx(), validate that the  
       supplied filename length is less than MAXPATHLEN. If the length exceeds  
       the limit, either truncate it or abort with an explicit error. This      
       moves the bug detection point to a well‑defined place in the code base.  
     3 Require length arguments – change the public API to accept an explicit   
       size_t length parameter and propagate length constraints throughout the  
       code base. This makes it impossible for callers to supply unbounded      
       strings without being aware of the limits.                               
     4 Compile‑time / run‑time hardening – enable and treat compiler warnings   
       (-Wunsafe-loop-optimization, -Wstringop-overflow) and sanitizers         
       (AddressSanitizer, StackProtector) as errors.  The sanitizers will       
       abort immediately on overflow, exposing the defect earlier.              
                                                                                
    These global changes make the program robust against path‑length overflows  
    in general, not just in the specific comprexx() case, thus preventing a     
    repeat of the demonstrated crash.                                           
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Answer in brief                                                             
                                                                                
     • Root cause: strcpy of an unbounded filename into a MAXPATHLEN byte       
       stack buffer overflows the buffer and corrupts the return address,       
       causing a crash.                                                         
     • Local fix: Use a bounded copy (strncpy/strlcpy) or explicit length       
       check before copying.                                                    
     • Global fix: Remove the fixed stack buffer entirely (or enforce strict    
       length checks earlier in the flow / redesign the API), avoiding          
       fixed‑size stack buffers as a general class‑wide security invariant.     
